1
00:00:05,462 --> 00:00:08,094
We've now reached 
a turning point in our studies

2
00:00:08,094 --> 00:00:10,885
of the cellular mechanisms 
of brain function.

3
00:00:11,690 --> 00:00:15,273
The purpose of brain function
is to govern behavior.

4
00:00:15,646 --> 00:00:19,072
We must now see to what extent
the biophysical mechanisms

5
00:00:19,072 --> 00:00:23,894
that we've studied over the last five weeks
are able to account for behavior.

6
00:00:24,954 --> 00:00:28,754
Let's begin by briefly reviewing
what we've learned.

7
00:00:29,191 --> 00:00:34,954
The brain is made of cells, each delimited
by a phospholipid bilayer.

8
00:00:36,313 --> 00:00:40,693
The cell membrane is impermeable to ions

9
00:00:41,443 --> 00:00:46,184
and so we can have charge separation
across the plasma membrane.

10
00:00:46,184 --> 00:00:49,779
The plasma membrane is
about five nanometers thick

11
00:00:49,779 --> 00:00:55,244
and so there can be strong electric fields
across this plasma membrane.

12
00:00:55,244 --> 00:00:59,564
That gives rise to membrane potential
and the electrical signals

13
00:00:59,564 --> 00:01:01,980
that we know underlie brain function.

14
00:01:03,564 --> 00:01:06,699
Charge movement
across the plasma membrane

15
00:01:06,699 --> 00:01:13,142
is mediated by ion channel proteins
that are inserted into the plasma membrane

16
00:01:13,142 --> 00:01:16,716
and they can have 
highly specific conductances

17
00:01:16,716 --> 00:01:19,827
for one species of ion, for example.

18
00:01:21,284 --> 00:01:27,338
These ion channels are not always open,
but rather, they are tightly regulated,

19
00:01:27,338 --> 00:01:30,532
and they have a certain open probability.

20
00:01:30,532 --> 00:01:34,016
Sometimes they're closed —
no current flow —

21
00:01:34,016 --> 00:01:37,338
and then they open and close again.

22
00:01:37,338 --> 00:01:40,841
That open probability
of these ion channels

23
00:01:40,841 --> 00:01:43,697
determines the net flux of ions

24
00:01:43,697 --> 00:01:48,639
and therefore the change in potential
across the plasma membrane.

25
00:01:49,311 --> 00:01:54,421
The tight regulation of ion channels
underlies the ability

26
00:01:54,421 --> 00:01:58,134
of electrical signals to occur
across the plasma membrane.

27
00:01:58,725 --> 00:02:03,738
In particular, we considered a class
of voltage-gated ion channels

28
00:02:03,738 --> 00:02:05,710
that's particularly useful

29
00:02:05,710 --> 00:02:09,862
in terms of making
the brief action potential signals

30
00:02:09,862 --> 00:02:13,806
that are an important way
of coding information in the brain.

31
00:02:15,151 --> 00:02:19,770
The voltage-gated sodium channel
increases its open probability

32
00:02:19,770 --> 00:02:24,690
steeply as the membrane potential
depolarizes more positive

33
00:02:24,690 --> 00:02:26,812
to around -40 millivolts.

34
00:02:27,995 --> 00:02:31,720
As the membrane potential depolarizes,
the open probability

35
00:02:31,720 --> 00:02:35,786
of the voltage-gated sodium channel
increases — that in turn causes

36
00:02:35,786 --> 00:02:41,389
more depolarization and that in turn
then increases the open probability

37
00:02:41,389 --> 00:02:43,530
of the voltage-gated sodium channel,

38
00:02:43,530 --> 00:02:47,038
generating the explosive depolarization

39
00:02:47,038 --> 00:02:50,189
of the cell towards the 
sodium reversal potential.

40
00:02:51,332 --> 00:02:56,682
The brief opening of the sodium channel,
its fast inactivation,

41
00:02:56,682 --> 00:02:59,780
and the delayed activation
of the potassium conductance

42
00:02:59,780 --> 00:03:05,333
drives repolarization and we're left 
with a brief all-or-none unitary signal,

43
00:03:05,333 --> 00:03:09,489
the action potential,
lasting about one millisecond.

44
00:03:10,589 --> 00:03:14,763
Nerve cells don't operate on their own;
they communicate with each other.

45
00:03:15,613 --> 00:03:19,082
Through the action potential
that propagates down the axon,

46
00:03:19,082 --> 00:03:24,273
invades specializations,
boutons, there's a release

47
00:03:24,273 --> 00:03:26,521
of a neurotransmitter substance

48
00:03:26,521 --> 00:03:31,181
that binds onto ligand-gated ion channels
in the postsynaptic neuron,

49
00:03:31,181 --> 00:03:34,871
in turn causing a change
in the membrane potential

50
00:03:34,871 --> 00:03:36,770
of that downstream neuron.

51
00:03:37,237 --> 00:03:41,662
So the action potential in one cell,
lasting about one millisecond,

52
00:03:41,662 --> 00:03:47,535
conveys a longer-lasting signal,
sub-threshold depolarization

53
00:03:47,535 --> 00:03:51,638
or hyperpolarization lasting
some tens of milliseconds

54
00:03:51,638 --> 00:03:54,556
interconnected downstream neurons.

55
00:03:55,349 --> 00:03:59,800
The process of synaptic transmission
is highly plastic.

56
00:03:59,800 --> 00:04:03,745
It depends on the previous history
of activity of that neuron

57
00:04:03,745 --> 00:04:06,959
and also depends
upon the overall experience

58
00:04:06,959 --> 00:04:08,690
of the animal.

59
00:04:08,690 --> 00:04:12,123
So there's that interesting
synaptic plasticity

60
00:04:12,123 --> 00:04:16,509
that occurs, and that in turn
appears to be the mechanism

61
00:04:16,509 --> 00:04:18,971
underlying learning and memory.

62
00:04:19,925 --> 00:04:22,669
So the individual neurons
communicate with each other

63
00:04:22,669 --> 00:04:27,711
and each neuron receives
inputs from many hundreds of neurons

64
00:04:27,711 --> 00:04:31,977
and in turn also delivers messages
to hundreds of neurons,

65
00:04:31,977 --> 00:04:37,113
some of which are widely distributed
across the neuronal circuits of the brain.

66
00:04:37,822 --> 00:04:42,337
We thus need to begin to divide
the neurons and the types of neurons.

67
00:04:42,337 --> 00:04:45,364
We know that there are 
excitatory glutamatergic neurons

68
00:04:45,364 --> 00:04:49,466
that release glutamate and try
to excite their postsynaptic targets.

69
00:04:49,466 --> 00:04:53,786
There are inhibitory GABAergic neurons
that release GABA

70
00:04:53,786 --> 00:04:55,658
and try to inhibit their targets.

71
00:04:55,658 --> 00:04:57,910
There are neuromodulatory neurons

72
00:04:57,910 --> 00:05:02,342
that release neuromodulators
that affect the dynamics and interactions

73
00:05:02,342 --> 00:05:06,396
of the system as well as the plasticity
of these neuronal circuits,

74
00:05:07,456 --> 00:05:10,859
and we need to deal then
with a great deal of complexity

75
00:05:10,859 --> 00:05:16,423
as to where and how these neurons
communicate in highly specific patterns

76
00:05:16,423 --> 00:05:19,095
and how they do so during behavior.

77
00:05:20,064 --> 00:05:24,372
So if our goal is to obtain
a causal understanding of behavior,

78
00:05:24,372 --> 00:05:28,588
we need to investigate brain function
at the level of individual neurons

79
00:05:28,588 --> 00:05:31,929
and their synaptic interactions —
that's how we're going to get

80
00:05:31,929 --> 00:05:35,264
a causal, mechanistic understanding —
and we need to do that

81
00:05:35,264 --> 00:05:37,239
within the complex neuronal networks

82
00:05:37,239 --> 00:05:41,101
of the living mammalian brain
during behavior.

83
00:05:42,151 --> 00:05:45,744
We need to see the action 
of the brain during action.

84
00:05:47,056 --> 00:05:48,325
So how are we going to do that?

85
00:05:48,919 --> 00:05:53,036
The first thing we need to be able to do
is to measure neuronal activity

86
00:05:53,036 --> 00:05:57,903
in the living brain and to correlate it
directly with ongoing behavior.

87
00:05:59,038 --> 00:06:04,292
At the level of cells and synapses,
there are two methods

88
00:06:04,292 --> 00:06:07,573
that so far have proved to be
extremely useful.

89
00:06:08,388 --> 00:06:11,702
One is the electrophysiological approach,

90
00:06:11,702 --> 00:06:15,689
where we introduce 
recording electrodes into the brain.

91
00:06:16,343 --> 00:06:19,220
We've already seen 
the whole-cell patch-clamp recording

92
00:06:19,220 --> 00:06:22,210
of membrane potential and currents

93
00:06:22,210 --> 00:06:25,454
that has been applied <i>in vitro</i>
in brain slices.

94
00:06:26,094 --> 00:06:29,242
It turns out that this method
can also be applied

95
00:06:29,242 --> 00:06:33,771
with small modifications
to study the brain in action —

96
00:06:33,771 --> 00:06:36,070
<i>in vivo</i>, during behavior.

97
00:06:37,555 --> 00:06:41,157
It also turns out to be possible
to make extracellular recordings

98
00:06:41,157 --> 00:06:42,962
of action potential firing.

99
00:06:42,962 --> 00:06:45,592
To date we've thought
of the extracellular solution

100
00:06:45,592 --> 00:06:49,886
as being at zero millivolts
isopotential and invariant.

101
00:06:49,886 --> 00:06:53,128
In fact, that turns out
not to be completely true,

102
00:06:53,128 --> 00:06:56,274
and there are small changes
in the extracellular potentials

103
00:06:56,274 --> 00:06:57,454
that can be recorded,

104
00:06:57,454 --> 00:06:59,971
and they can be recorded
relatively easily.

105
00:06:59,971 --> 00:07:03,923
The inference of which cell
is firing action potentials

106
00:07:03,923 --> 00:07:05,249
can also be made.

107
00:07:05,708 --> 00:07:08,924
The extracellular recordings
are technically easier

108
00:07:08,924 --> 00:07:13,288
than the intracellular recordings,
and so one can in parallel record

109
00:07:13,288 --> 00:07:16,520
from many neurons at the same time
and study network function

110
00:07:16,520 --> 00:07:18,911
using extracellular recordings.

111
00:07:20,776 --> 00:07:24,336
Electrophysiological measurements
are certainly proving useful

112
00:07:24,336 --> 00:07:27,407
in correlating neuronal activity
with behavior.

113
00:07:28,137 --> 00:07:31,951
However, in the electrophysiology,
we need to introduce

114
00:07:31,951 --> 00:07:34,279
recording electrodes into the brain.

115
00:07:34,279 --> 00:07:37,148
These recording electrodes
must have some size,

116
00:07:37,148 --> 00:07:40,654
and that in turn perturbs the brain.

117
00:07:42,448 --> 00:07:44,901
It's interesting to think
about other techniques

118
00:07:44,901 --> 00:07:48,316
that might be less invasive,
and introducing photons

119
00:07:48,316 --> 00:07:52,420
into the brain is one
of the most interesting techniques

120
00:07:52,420 --> 00:07:54,921
that is being developed at the moment

121
00:07:54,921 --> 00:07:57,395
for studying brain function
at high resolution.

122
00:07:57,954 --> 00:08:03,045
So optical imaging techniques,
and in particular fluorescence microscopy,

123
00:08:03,045 --> 00:08:04,897
is turning out to be extremely interesting

124
00:08:04,897 --> 00:08:09,162
in terms of getting high-resolution
structural and functional measurements

125
00:08:09,162 --> 00:08:12,653
of the brain, and at this time
this is possible to do

126
00:08:12,653 --> 00:08:15,674
in the living brain
and correlate it with behavior.

127
00:08:16,436 --> 00:08:20,028
In later videos of this week,
we'll study how we can apply

128
00:08:20,028 --> 00:08:25,355
electrophysiological measurements
in video 6.3 and how we can apply

129
00:08:25,355 --> 00:08:28,502
optical methods for investigating

130
00:08:29,422 --> 00:08:32,398
neuronal activity in video 6.4.

131
00:08:33,027 --> 00:08:35,525
So we're beginning to have methods

132
00:08:35,525 --> 00:08:39,117
for measuring and correlating
neuronal activity with behavior.

133
00:08:39,117 --> 00:08:42,163
That's absolutely essential
as a starting point.

134
00:08:42,163 --> 00:08:46,104
But correlations 
don't necessarily imply causality,

135
00:08:46,884 --> 00:08:49,302
and so if we want to investigate
the causal impact

136
00:08:49,302 --> 00:08:51,337
of a specific neuronal activity,

137
00:08:51,337 --> 00:08:54,088
we need to specifically 
perturb that activity.

138
00:08:54,088 --> 00:08:58,640
We need to be able to take control
of the neurons and the neuronal circuits

139
00:08:58,640 --> 00:09:01,786
and see what effect 
that has upon behavior.

140
00:09:03,098 --> 00:09:06,082
That's turned out to be
an extremely difficult problem

141
00:09:06,082 --> 00:09:09,718
to have highly specific
interventions in the brain.

142
00:09:09,718 --> 00:09:13,162
So typically, one has relied upon lesions,

143
00:09:13,162 --> 00:09:18,970
brain damages, diseases, stimulation 
or pharmacological manipulations,

144
00:09:18,970 --> 00:09:23,272
and all of these lack specificity
in space and time.

145
00:09:24,446 --> 00:09:28,834
So it's been difficult to get
a real detailed information

146
00:09:28,834 --> 00:09:33,134
about the causal impact
of specific types of neuronal activity.

147
00:09:33,150 --> 00:09:37,036
Over the last years, there's been
a revolution in neuroscience

148
00:09:37,036 --> 00:09:39,791
that's been driven by <i>optogenetics</i>,

149
00:09:39,791 --> 00:09:44,100
a way in which we can control
neuronal activity by light.

150
00:09:45,124 --> 00:09:49,023
This occurs through expressing
specific light-sensitive proteins

151
00:09:49,023 --> 00:09:52,909
that can then affect
