154
00:09:59,839 --> 00:10:05,867
on specific neurons or parts of neurons
gaining high spatiotemporal resolution.

155
00:10:05,867 --> 00:10:08,915
So there's a great deal of hope now
that we'll be able to make

156
00:10:08,915 --> 00:10:12,839
highly specific perturbations
during behavior,

157
00:10:12,839 --> 00:10:16,191
and then we'll be able
to study the impact of that.

158
00:10:17,392 --> 00:10:22,468
So if we're able to make 
measurements and perturbations

159
00:10:22,468 --> 00:10:25,227
of highly specific neuronal activities,

160
00:10:25,227 --> 00:10:27,863
the next step is to try and see

161
00:10:27,863 --> 00:10:30,750
how those measurements 
and perturbations fit together.

162
00:10:31,270 --> 00:10:35,123
In order to do that, we need
to quantitatively model the phenomenon

163
00:10:35,873 --> 00:10:38,986
and that then will give us
causal mechanistic insight

164
00:10:38,986 --> 00:10:41,669
and allow us to test specific hypotheses.

165
00:10:43,542 --> 00:10:47,390
Unfortunately, we currently have
a very incomplete understanding

166
00:10:47,390 --> 00:10:49,920
of neuronal circuits
in the mammalian brain.

167
00:10:49,920 --> 00:10:54,246
We're very far from having
a quantitative mechanistic understanding

168
00:10:54,246 --> 00:10:57,292
of even the very simplest behaviors.

169
00:10:57,802 --> 00:11:01,811
So the starting point is far
from where we want to be.

170
00:11:03,278 --> 00:11:06,829
Of course, the brain 
